===Scaled correlation coefficient===
Scaled correlation is a variant of Pearson&#x27;s correlation in which the range of the data is restricted intentionally and in a controlled manner to reveal correlations between fast components in time series. Scaled correlation is defined as average correlation across short segments of data.

Let formula_114 be the number of segments that can fit into the total length of the signal formula_115 for a given scale formula_116:

:formula_117

The scaled correlation across the entire signals formula_118 is then computed as

:formula_119

where formula_120 is Pearson&#x27;s coefficient of correlation for segment formula_121.

By choosing the parameter formula_116, the range of values is reduced and the correlations on long time scale are filtered out, only the correlations on short time scales being revealed. Thus, the contributions of slow components are removed and those of fast components are retained.

===Pearson&#x27;s distance===
A distance metric for two variables &quot;X&quot; and &quot;Y&quot; known as &quot;Pearson&#x27;s distance&quot; can be defined from their correlation coefficient as
:formula_123
Considering that the Pearson correlation coefficient falls between [−1, +1], the Pearson distance lies in [0, 2]. The Pearson distance has been used in cluster analysis and data detection for communications and storage with unknown gain and offset.

The Pearson &quot;distance&quot; defined this way assigns distance greater than 1 to negative correlations. In reality, both strong positive correlation and negative correlations are meaningful, so care must be taken when Pearson &quot;distance&quot; is used for nearest neighbor algorithm as such algorithm will only include neighbors with positive correlation and exclude neighbors with negative correlation. Alternatively, an absolute valued distance, formula_124, can be applied, which will take both positive and negative correlations into consideration. The information on positive and negative association can be extracted separately, later.

===Circular correlation coefficient===
For variables &quot;X&quot; = {&quot;x&quot;1...,&quot;x&quot;&quot;n&quot;} and &quot;Y&quot; = {&quot;y&quot;1...,&quot;y&quot;&quot;n&quot;} that are defined on the unit circle , it is possible to define a circular analog of Pearson&#x27;s coefficient. This is done by transforming data points in &quot;X&quot; and &quot;Y&quot; with a sine function such that the correlation coefficient is given as:

:formula_125

where formula_126 and formula_32 are the circular means of &quot;X&quot; and &quot;Y&quot;. This measure can be useful in fields like meteorology where the angular direction of data is important.

===Partial correlation===

If a population or data-set is characterized by more than two variables, a partial correlation coefficient measures the strength of dependence between a pair of variables that is not accounted for by the way in which they both change in response to variations in a selected subset of the other variables.

